&gt; 
&gt;&gt;Memory use (and traffic to disk) is more a function of the
&gt;&gt;number of hosts/queues that have been discovered or active,
&gt;&gt;than of the total number of URLs discovered or crawled. So
&gt;&gt;any &#39;broader&#39; crawls will strain resources more than
&gt;&gt;&#39;narrower&#39; ones with a smaller or fixed number of hosts
&gt;&gt;of interest.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;Your machine may be swapping heavily. Things to check:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;  - Does &#39;top&#39; show swap in use?
&gt;&gt;  - How does your configured max heap and current heap size
&gt;&gt;    compare with RAM? (Max heap should be 25% or more smaller
&gt;&gt;  - Do the &#39;si&#39; and &#39;so&#39; columns in &#39;vmstat 2&#39;
&gt;&gt;    (sample every 2 seconds) show activity?
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;Separately from OS virtual memory, the new BDB/soft-reference
&gt;&gt;mechanism for &#39;paging&#39; per-host/per-queue data out when not in
&gt;&gt;immediate use could theoretically reach some excessive IO states
&gt;&gt;in low-memory conditions. This would be more likely if you weren&#39;t
&gt;&gt;using the &#39;hold-queues&#39; setting and were instead round-robinning
&gt;&gt;among all queues in a big crawl.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;- Gordon @ IA
